      {
        "name": "pageInfoParagraph",
        "isParent": true,
        "data": {
          "header": "What is Ludo ?",
          "cssClassList": ["middle-para-new"],
          "contentList": [
            "Ludo board game needs no introduction to the Indian audience. A game that is still fondly played by many on the traditional board, enjoyed sort of a renaissance in 2020 as its popularity grew exponentially.",
            "For those unaware, Ludo is a board game that is played between 2 to 4 players. The objective of the Ludo game is to be the first to move your four pieces/tokens from the starting area to the finishing point. This is achieved by rolling the dice, moving your pieces on the board, evading being cut by your opponent’s pieces and reaching the respective coloured destination."
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "name": "pageInfoParagraph",
        "isParent": true,
        "data": {
          "header": "How to Play Ludo on vpl ?",
          "cssClassList": ["middle-para-new"],
          "contentList": [
            "<img src='/static/banners/ludo-play.png'/> <br/> <br/>Ludo on vpl can be played on both Android and iOS smartphones. While Ludo is a game that is generally played for fun, on vpl, players have the opportunity to compete with online players for real cash. The higher the number of wins, the greater the reward.",
            "Currently, on the vpl app,<a href=/ludo> online Ludo </a> is available in battle mode. In battles, a player competes to score better than other opponents. Players competing in several Ludo matches accumulate scores based on their wins. Number of wins determines a player’s rank on the leaderboard. The top players win handsome cash rewards."
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "name": "pageInfoParagraph",
        "isParent": true,
        "data": {
          "header": "Understanding Ludo Gameplay",
          "cssClassList": ["middle-para-new"],
          "contentList": [
            "The Rummy Declare Rules state that once a player has arranged his hand into combinations of sets and sequences, he can declare the game. At this point, the player will be allotted a time frame to meld in cards into the combinations, post which the combinations are validated before announcing the winner. "
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "name": "RummyFaqs",
        "isParent": true,
        "data": {
          "header": "",
          "cssClassList": ["white-backgound"],
          "faqsList": [
            {
              "header": "Board and Pieces",
              "subParagraphes": [
                "Traditional Ludo makes use of a board, designed specifically for the game. It has four coloured sections (red, green, yellow and blue) in each of the corners, called as the starting zones; and in the centre, called as the home area. The rest is the white squared path which the player uses to move his pieces from start to finish. <br/> Speaking of pieces, there are four different coloured pieces (same as the coloured zones). There are four pieces each of every colour. Lastly, players make use of dice, the scores of which are used to make the moves."
              ]
            },
            {
              "header": "The Start",
              "subParagraphes": [
                "As mentioned, Ludo can be played by 2 to 4 players. In the online mode, whenever the player enters the game, he/she is matched with available online players to start the game. At the start, each player is given pieces of a specific colour (red, green, yellow and blue), all of which are positioned inside their respective starting areas. Here are some <a href=/ludo/tips-to-play-ludo> tips to play </a> ludo which you must know."
              ]
            },
            {
              "header": "Navigation",
              "subParagraphes": [
                "Players must take turns to throw the dice. It is done by clicking on the dice icon on the screen. Alternatively, the player can also set it on ‘Auto’ which means the dice will automatically be thrown when it is the player’s turn, as per the normal sequence of ludo gameplay on vpl.",
                "A score of 6 is required to move a piece out of its starting area, post which the player can move the piece freely on the board, the goal being to cross all opponent areas and reach the final destination. Rolling another 6 on the dice grants an extra turn to the player. However, if a player gets a 6 three times in a row, he will be forced to forfeit his turn.",
                "Players can open the other three pieces when they get 6s. The choice remains on the player, if he wants to move one of his pieces ahead or take a piece out of the starting area.",
                "A player can cut an opponent’s token by having his/her piece occupy the same area as the opponent’s. This will result in the opponent’s piece being sent back to the starting area. The opponent will need to score another 6 or 1 to take that piece out. This is the fundamental strategy of Ludo, which can also be used by your opponents to eliminate your tokens from the route.",
                "Tokens can be cut from anywhere on the path except in the safe zone and when it has reached its coloured area. There are a total of 8 safe zones in the map, specifically marked to be easily identifiable. The safe zone can also be strategically used to wait for the opponent’s token and cut"
              ]
            },
            {
              "header": "Winning The Game",
              "subParagraphes": [
                "As you must have read, despite Ludo being a pretty straight forward game, there still remains a lot of intricacies involved with the game. It is very important to know the<a href='/ludo/rules-of-ludo'> rules of ludo </a> so that you don't make any mistake. Mastering the basics of Ludo, is the first step for players looking to be a pro Ludo player on vpl."
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      },
